The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Bengal ahead of tax target 
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       Bengal ahead of tax target 
          A STAFF REPORTER                                          
	Calcutta, April 14: Bengals income tax collection has exceeded its annual target for the first time in the last 10 years, underlining a good performance of the state economy, though growth in tax collections was less than the national average.        
	Compared with the target of Rs 11,638 crore for the Bengal circle, which also includes a nominal contribution from Sikkim and the Andaman and Nicobar Islands, the I-T department has collected Rs 12,019 crore in 2007-08. In the last year, it was Rs 9,770.75 crore.        
	Income tax chief commissioner T.K. Chatterjee said the number could go up by another Rs 600 crore when the final tally was prepared. Corporate tax collection went up 19.41 per cent, while personal income tax rose 33.13 per cent over the last year, taking the overall growth to 23.02 per cent.        
	Though it trails the estimated national average growth of over 30 per cent  the final figures are yet to come  industry was happy that the target was topped for the first time in a decade.        
	This clearly indicates there is buoyancy in the economy. All the eastern region companies are doing well. Compliance has gone up as healthy growth in personal I-T numbers show, Biswadip Gupta, chairman of CII (eastern region), said.         
	Of the total Rs 12,019 crore, collection from Calcutta alone stood at Rs 11,500 crore, indicating that Bengals economy is still Calcutta-centric.        
	Personal I-T collection this year stood at Rs 3,417 crore compared with Rs 2,566.65 crore last year.         
	Among companies, ITC paid the most tax at Rs 1,685.66 crore, followed by Coal India at Rs 484.77 crore.         
	Other top tax payers are Damodar Valley Corporation, Rungta Mines, Essel Mining and Industries, Allahabad Bank, the West Bengal Infrastructure Development Finance Corporation, Birla Corporation, Exide, EIH, Kesoram Industries, Calcutta Port Trust, the Orissa Minerals Development Corporation and Tata Tea.                                                                                                                                      
